==German==

===Alternative forms===
* {{alter|de|bey}}

===Etymology===
From {{inh|de|gmh|bī}}, from {{inh|de|goh|bī}}, from {{inh|de|gmw-pro|*bī}}, from {{inh|de|gem-pro|*bi}}. More at {{l|en|by}}.

===Pronunciation===
* {{IPA|de|/baɪ̯/}}
* {{rhymes|de|aɪ̯|s=1}}
* {{audio|de|De-bei.ogg|audio}}

===Preposition===
{{head|de|preposition|+ dative}}

# {{lb|de|locative}} [[by]]; [[near]]
#: {{uxi|de|die Bank '''bei''' der Kirche|the bench/bank '''by''' the church}}
#: {{uxi|de|die Bäckerei '''beim''' Bahnhof|the bakery '''near''' the train station}}
# {{lb|de|with a person, family, shop}} [[at]]
#: {{uxi|de|Ich schlafe '''bei''' Peter.|I’m sleeping '''at''' Peter’s [place].}}
#: {{uxi|de|Ich bin '''beim''' Metzger.|I'm '''at''' the butcher’s.}}
# {{lb|de|with an organization or company}} [[for]]; [[at]]; [[in]]
#: {{uxi|de|'''bei''' der Firma arbeiten|to work '''for''' the firm}}
#: {{ux|de|das Arbeitsklima '''bei''' Schmidt & Co.|the working atmosphere '''at''' Schmidt & Co.}}
# {{lb|de|formal|reflexive}} [[with]]; [[on]]
#: {{uxi|de|Er hat es nicht '''bei''' sich.|He doesn’t have it '''on''' him.}}
#:: → for which usually: ''Er hat es nicht {{m|de|dabei}}.''
# {{lb|de|with an event considered certain}} [[upon]], at the time of
#: {{uxi|de|'''bei''' Abfahrt des Zuges|'''upon''' departure of the train}}
# {{lb|de|with an event considered theoretical}} [[in case]] of, in the event of
#: {{uxi|de|'''bei''' Hochwasser|'''in case of''' flooding}}
# {{lb|de|with a continuing activity or condition}} [[during]]; [[while]]; during the existence of
#: {{uxi|de|'''bei''' der Arbeit|'''during''' work}}
#: {{uxi|de|'''beim''' Lesen des Textes|'''while''' reading the text}}
#: {{uxi|de|'''bei''' Schnee|'''when there is''' snow}}
# {{lb|de|with an item that implies an activity}} [[over]]; [[during]]
#: {{uxi|de|'''bei''' einem Glas Wein|'''over''' a glass of wine (that is, ''while'' drinking it)}}
#: {{uxi|de|'''bei''' einem Film|'''during''' a film (that is, ''while'' watching it)}}
# {{lb|de|dated|in a postal address}} [[care of]]
#: {{uxi|de|Frau Tina Müller '''bei''' Firma Schmidt & Co.|Mrs Tina Müller, '''care of''' Schmidt & Co.}}
# {{lb|de|now|_|dialectal|nonstandard|northern and central Germany|with <u>accusative</u>}} [[with]], [[to]], [[towards]]
#: {{uxi|de|Leg dat '''bei''' die andern Sachen!|Put that '''with''' the other things!}}
#: {{uxi|de|Komm ma '''bei''' mich!|Come '''to''' me!}}

====Usage notes====
* When {{m|de|bei}} is followed by the definite article {{m|de|dem||the}}, the two words contract to {{m|de|beim}}. However, when {{m|de|dem}} is a demonstrative pronoun, no contraction occurs. Compare:
:: ''Der Baum steht zu nah '''beim''' Haus.'' – “The tree is too close to the house.”
:: ''Der Baum steht zu nah '''bei dem''' Haus da hinten.'' – “The tree is too close to that house over there.”
* {{sense|with, to, towards}} In many dialects, and historically in literary style, {{m|de|bei}} could express movement, requiring then the accusative case. This is in conflict with modern standard rules, for which reason this use of the preposition is becoming rare. In adverbial constructions, however, {{m|de||bei}} and {{m|de|dabei}} expressing movement are still fairly common in regional speech: ''Kommt noch was '''dabei'''?'' (“Do you want anything else with that?”) ''Sie können Sie sich hier ruhig '''bei'''setzen.'' (“You may come sit here with us.”) The standard language proper normally uses {{m|de|dazu}} in such cases, but it does feature some relicts in compounds such as {{m|de|herbei}}, {{m|de|beiseite}}, {{m|de|beilegen}}, {{m|de|beitreten}}, etc. Compare also the idiom {{m|de|Butter bei die Fische}}. Compare further {{cog|nl|bij}} for which all such constructions are perfectly standard.

